Exploratory Data Analysis

In this exploratory data analysis (EDA), we examine the time series data sets discussed in the Data Visualization section. The goal is to gain insight into the underlying components of the multiple time series. These analyses include trends, seasonality, variations, and periodic fluctuations. In addition, we will evaluate the time series for decomposition to see if it can be identified as multiplicative or additive. We will analyze the data sets using the following time series plots and tools: Lag plots, autocorrelation function (ACF) and partial autocorrelation function (PACF) analysis, stationarity checks using the Augmented Dickey-Fuller test, and Moving Average Smoothing for several periods of time.

Global Oil Production

The following plot, shows the data for the top 15 oil-producing countries in 2022. The goal is to use a line plot to show the evolution of the global oil market over the last 22 years and identify the dynamic leaders. Throughout this project, our central focus will be on the United States, which has been the leading country in oil production since 2018.


In the Exploratory Data Analisis | U.S Oil Production section, we conducted an examination of the time series dataset. Focusing on the data from 01-01-2000, our initial assessment included testing for stationarity using the ACF plot and the Augmented Dickey-Fuller test, which revealed significant autocorrelation in the lags. To address this, a first difference was applied to the time series, resulting in a visually stationary plot. With this result, we are ready to use the time series data for analysis.

Oil Price by Month

Price is a key characteristic to analyze in order to understand the behavior of a product in the market. One relevant dataset that has been included is the price of crude oil. In the Exploratory Data Analisis | Oil Price section, we focused on gaining valuable insights into market dynamics and trends through a time series lens. The first steps involved data cleaning, where NA values were addressed through exponential imputation. We then applied Moving Average Smoothing with three different time periods to create insightful charts. Although significant fluctuations were observed, no clear trend emerged for the entire time frame.

To assess stationarity, we used the ACF plot and the Augmented Dickey-Fuller test, which revealed high autocorrelation in the lags. Implementing a first difference, as shown in the plot below, made the time series stationary, improving its suitability for further analysis and modeling.

Bus Transport

Bus transport is a key component of our analysis as it represents a great proportion of the transportation industry. In the Exploratory Data Analisis | Bus Passenger Trips section, we focused on gaining valuable insights into market dynamics and trends through a time series lens. We applied Moving Average Smoothing with three different time periods to create insightful charts. By observing the plot for the Pre-COVID, we conclude that there is no clear trend for al the periods selected. By observing the plot for the complete analysis we can see the first two plots show that there is no clear trend for the behaviour of bus passengers for the years before 2020. Due to the covid pandemic, we can clearly see the trend affected, tending to a negative value.

  • Pre-COVID Analysis
  • Complete Analysis

For both cases to assess stationarity, we used the ACF plot and the Augmented Dickey-Fuller test, which revealed high autocorrelation in the lags. To achieve stationarity we applied a seasonal difference equal to 10.
